\f3\b\fs36 Intro To Game Designing
\f1\b0\fs28 \
\
Welcome, and congratulations on getting this far! Most people who develop an interest in designing their own RPG give up before they even begin! There are some who might get as far as to learn a bit of programming, but they soon abandon all their hopes and dreams of moulding their very own dungeon exploring, treasure finding, monster slaying, EXP earning, level raising RPG because they get frustrated at not being able to program any of the things they want their game to have. It\'d5s a sad fact that this problem is usually caused by people being impatient, and quite often lazy.\
\
The golden rule to remember is: start small. The reason why people can\'d5t program their super cool 100mb RPG right away on day one is simply that they don\'d5t know enough about programming. Get experience by making a few small games before you attempt the next World of Warcraft, and get used to the application you\'d5re using to create them with. (in this case Mac GameMaker, and it couldn\'d5t be a better choice)\
\
I myself rushed into RPG designing the moment I got my hands on my first game editor years and years ago. I didn\'d5t understand anything about programming so the game was a complete flop! However I continued searching for and downloading game editors, hoping that one of them would do for what I wanted. Little did I know that any one of them would have done for what I wanted. The problem was that I was trying to find a magic editor that would put everything I wanted into the game for me at the click of a few buttons, when what I 
\f4\i should
\f1\i0  have been doing was learning programming.\
\
Programming isn\'d5t that hard to learn at all, in fact provided you\'d5ve got a good language (like Mac GameMaker\'d5s) it\'d5s quite simple. Once you know the rules that apply to it you can make pretty much any kind of game you like! This guide will help you get started creating your own RPG, but before you continue I advise you to spend a few days or a week getting used to Mac GameMaker\'d5s programming language. Make a few small games, get to know a few of the commands and variables, and what a variable 
\f4\i is
\f1\i0 , hehe. Don\'d5t worry, I\'d5ll wait for you...\
\
\

\f3\b\fs36 Tutorial On Mac GameMaker's Language
\f1\b0\fs28 \
\
